    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-10-16T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-10-16T11:00:00-05:00" n="605"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d605">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/6082: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-16T19:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 16, 1940—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1355. The press today publishes a Tass communiqué denying as “not in accordance
                    with the facts” a report stated to have appeared in the Danish newspaper under
                        [<hi rend="italic">sic</hi>] <hi rend="italic">Politiken</hi> from its
                    Berlin correspondent to the effect that the Soviet Government was informed “in
                    due time that German forces were to be sent to Rumania and that the Kremlin was
                    informed as to the stand of these forces and as to the purposes for which they
                    were sent to Rumania.”<note n="36" xml:id="d605fn36">With regard to the presence
                        of German troops in Rumania, see telegrams Nos. 579, October 7, 6 p.m., and
                        585, October 9, 5 p.m., from the Minister in Rumania, <ref target="#pg_519"
                            >pp. 519</ref> and <ref target="#pg_520">520</ref>, respectively.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated to Berlin and Bucharest.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
